\subsection{The Data}\label{the-data}

For this project, we use data provided by Yelp for the Yelp Dataset
challenge, which can be found in JSON format from this website:

We then merge it with Zillow data on rental values across the United
States and Canada by postal code. The Zillow rental value dataset can be
downloaded from this website:

\subsection{Reshaping the data}\label{reshaping-the-data}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_flat_long <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{reshape}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_flat, }\DataTypeTok{varying =} \KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_flat[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{:}\DecValTok{168}\NormalTok{])), }\DataTypeTok{times =} \KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_flat[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{:}\DecValTok{168}\NormalTok{]), }\DataTypeTok{idvar =} \StringTok{'business_id'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{v.names =} \StringTok{'checkin'} \NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{direction =} \StringTok{'long'}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_flat_long$time <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{str_replace}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_flat_long$time, }\StringTok{"time."}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_flat_long$time <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{gsub}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'[[:digit:]]+'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{''}\NormalTok{, yelp_checkin_flat_long$time)}

\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_flat_long$time =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{substr}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_flat_long$time,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\KeywordTok{nchar}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_flat_long$time)-}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Here, we will collapse the data, reshape it from long to wide, then
merge them together

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_collapse_mean <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{aggregate}\NormalTok{(checkin ~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{business_id +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{time, yelp_checkin_flat_long , mean))}
\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_collapse_sum <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{aggregate}\NormalTok{(checkin ~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{business_id +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{time, yelp_checkin_flat_long , sum))}

\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_wide_mean <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{spread}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_collapse_mean, }\DataTypeTok{key =} \NormalTok{time, }\DataTypeTok{value =} \NormalTok{checkin)}
\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_wide_sum <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{spread}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_collapse_sum, }\DataTypeTok{key =} \NormalTok{time, }\DataTypeTok{value =} \NormalTok{checkin)}

\NormalTok{yelp_checkin_wide <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{inner_join}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_wide_mean, yelp_checkin_wide_sum, }\DataTypeTok{by=}\StringTok{'business_id'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{match=}\StringTok{'all'}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{colnames}\NormalTok{(yelp_checkin_wide) <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"business_id"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Friday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Monday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Saturday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Sunday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Thursday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Tuesday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Wednesday_ave"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Friday_total"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Monday_total"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Saturday_total"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Sunday_total"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Thursday_total"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Tuesday_total"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Wednesday_total"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{Zillow data}\label{zillow-data}

Here, we read in the Zillow data that has information on all rental
values across the US and Canada. We will rename the RegionName variable
to ``postal\_code'' then convert the data from wide to long in order to
merge it with the Yelp dataset. We will change the ``time'' variable to
a date class, and finally we cut the Zillow data to match the dates of
the Yelp data (while Zillow data goes back to the 1990s, Yelp business
and review data only go back to 2010).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{zillow <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read_csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"zecon/Zip_Zri_AllHomesPlusMultifamily.csv"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{col_names =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_integer(),
##   RegionName = col_character(),
##   City = col_character(),
##   State = col_character(),
##   Metro = col_character(),
##   CountyName = col_character()
## )
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{names} \NormalTok{(zillow)[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "postal_code"}
\NormalTok{zillow <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.data.frame}\NormalTok{(zillow)}
\NormalTok{zillow_long <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{reshape}\NormalTok{(zillow, }\DataTypeTok{varying =} \KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(zillow[}\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{:}\DecValTok{95}\NormalTok{])), }\DataTypeTok{times =} \KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(zillow[}\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{:}\DecValTok{95}\NormalTok{]), }\DataTypeTok{idvar =} \StringTok{'postal_code'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{v.names =} \StringTok{'rentprice'} \NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{direction =} \StringTok{'long'}\NormalTok{)}

\KeywordTok{sapply}\NormalTok{(zillow_long, function(x) }\KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(x)))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Notice that there is some missingness; i.e., 28,354 missing values. }

\NormalTok{zillow_long$time<-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{strptime}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{paste}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, zillow_long$time),}\StringTok{"%d %Y-%m"}\NormalTok{))}

\NormalTok{zillow_long <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{zillow_long[zillow_long$time >=}\StringTok{ "2010-11-01"} \NormalTok{&}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{zillow_long$time <=}\StringTok{ "2017-12-31"}\NormalTok{,]}

\NormalTok{zillow_long$month <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{match}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{months}\NormalTok{(zillow_long$time), month.name)}
\NormalTok{zillow_long$year <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{format}\NormalTok{(zillow_long$time,}\DataTypeTok{format=}\StringTok{"%Y"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{zillow_long$YearMonth <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.yearmon}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{paste}\NormalTok{(zillow_long$year, zillow_long$month), }\StringTok{"%Y %m"}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(zillow_long)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}

\NormalTok{temp <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{row.names}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{as.data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(Full_data_long$City, }\DataTypeTok{max=}\DecValTok{12}\NormalTok{))) }\CommentTok{# create a df or something else with the summary output.}

This counts the ``cateories'' included in the dataset. These categories
are tags users might use to describe various businesses. We can that the
top category is ``Restuarants'' followed by ``Shopping,'' ``Food,''
``Home Services,'' and ``Beauty and Spa.''

The Yelp dataset includes information on businesses that may have been
open but are currently closed. The previous analyses included all of
them, but here we assess the counts of categories only for buinesses
that are open.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{catplot_open <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{business_zillow %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(-}\KeywordTok{starts_with}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"hours"}\NormalTok{), -}\KeywordTok{starts_with}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"attribute"}\NormalTok{)) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(is_open==}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{unnest}\NormalTok{(categories) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(name, categories) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(categories) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{summarise}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{n=}\KeywordTok{n}\NormalTok{()) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{desc}\NormalTok{(n)) %>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{head}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{catplot_open  <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.data.frame}\NormalTok{(catplot_open )}

\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{data=}\NormalTok{catplot_open , }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x=}\NormalTok{categories, }\DataTypeTok{y=}\NormalTok{n)) +}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_bar}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{stat=}\StringTok{"identity"}\NormalTok{) +}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{theme}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{axis.text.x =} \KeywordTok{element_text}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{angle =} \DecValTok{90}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{hjust =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)) +}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{title=}\StringTok{"Frequency of Open Categories in Dataset"}\NormalTok{) +}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{xlab}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Category"}\NormalTok{) +}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{ylab}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Count"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Final_RMD_Script_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-4-1.pdf}

Top categories include: Restaurants, Shopping, Home Services, Food,
Health \& Medical. Interestingly, it seems like ``Food'' and ``Beauty \&
Spas'' might be closing at higher rate than other categories.

\subsection{Modeling and Panel Data Regression
Analysis}\label{modeling-and-panel-data-regression-analysis}

Now comes the fun part. We split the data into train and test sets where
our test set comprises the last year (12 months) or our data set. We run
a Hausman test to determine whether we should run a fixed effects
(``within'') or a random effects model. Then we develop a Panel Linear
Regression model to predict housing prices.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Full_data_long_train <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Full_data_long[Full_data_long$time <}\StringTok{ "2017-01-01"}\NormalTok{,]}
\NormalTok{Full_data_long_test <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Full_data_long[Full_data_long$time >=}\StringTok{ "2017-01-01"}\NormalTok{,]}

\NormalTok{my.formula <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{rentprice ~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{starsav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{is_openave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{funnyav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{coolav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{usefulav }
\NormalTok{my.index <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'postal_code'}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{'time'}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{my.hausman.test.train <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{phtest}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =} \NormalTok{my.formula, }
                          \DataTypeTok{data =} \NormalTok{Full_data_long_train,}
                          \DataTypeTok{model =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'within'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'random'}\NormalTok{),}
                          \DataTypeTok{index =} \NormalTok{my.index)}
\KeywordTok{print}\NormalTok{(my.hausman.test.train)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## 
##  Hausman Test
## 
## data:  my.formula
## chisq = 1.2796, df = 5, p-value = 0.937
## alternative hypothesis: one model is inconsistent
\end{verbatim}

The high p-value of 0.937 indicates that we should use a random effects
model instead of a fixed effects model.

Now, we build our random effects model on the training dataset and
predict on the test set. We calculate the Mean Averege Percent Error
(MAPE) to see how accurately our model use training values to predict
rental prices in the test set.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my.pdm.train <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{plm}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{data =} \NormalTok{Full_data_long_train, }
              \DataTypeTok{formula =} \NormalTok{my.formula, }
              \DataTypeTok{model =} \StringTok{'random'}\NormalTok{,}
              \DataTypeTok{index =} \NormalTok{my.index)}
\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(my.pdm.train)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## Oneway (individual) effect Random Effect Model 
##    (Swamy-Arora's transformation)
## 
## Call:
## plm(formula = my.formula, data = Full_data_long_train, model = "random", 
##     index = my.index)
## 
## Unbalanced Panel: n = 560, T = 1-74, N = 31397
## 
## Effects:
##                     var   std.dev share
## idiosyncratic   6321.76     79.51 0.023
## individual    270893.25    520.47 0.977
## theta:
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.8490  0.9817  0.9822  0.9806  0.9822  0.9822 
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -2126.91   -40.27    -6.88    -0.36    37.76  2068.60 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error  t-value  Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 1238.62701   22.65028  54.6848 < 2.2e-16 ***
## starsav       -2.85126    0.83058  -3.4329  0.000598 ***
## is_openave   131.20358    3.13631  41.8337 < 2.2e-16 ***
## funnyav      -10.17243    0.86013 -11.8266 < 2.2e-16 ***
## coolav        11.10536    0.96571  11.4997 < 2.2e-16 ***
## usefulav     -11.10133    0.42243 -26.2800 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Total Sum of Squares:    226790000
## Residual Sum of Squares: 203110000
## R-Squared:      0.10443
## Adj. R-Squared: 0.10429
## F-statistic: 731.838 on 5 and 31391 DF, p-value: < 2.22e-16
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Full_data_long_test$pred.plm.test <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{predict}\NormalTok{(my.pdm.train, Full_data_long_test, }\DataTypeTok{type=}\StringTok{'response'}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{plmmape <-}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{*}\KeywordTok{mean}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{abs}\NormalTok{(Full_data_long_test$pred.plm.test/Full_data_long_test$rentprice}\DecValTok{-1}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =} \NormalTok{T)}
\KeywordTok{print}\NormalTok{(plmmape)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{Generating the Lag Model}\label{generating-the-lag-model}

To fine-tune the model, we decide to lag the dependent variable to
consider the possibility that last month's rent could be the best
predictor of this month's rent price. We follow a similar process to the
one above for training, testing, and predicting.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my.lag.formula <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{rentprice ~}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{lag}\NormalTok{(rentprice, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{starsav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{is_openave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{funnyav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{coolav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{usefulav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Number_of_reviews}

\CommentTok{# Conduct Hausman Test}
\NormalTok{my.hausman.test.train.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{phtest}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =} \NormalTok{my.lag.formula, }
                                \DataTypeTok{data =} \NormalTok{Full_data_long_train,}
                                \DataTypeTok{model =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'within'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'random'}\NormalTok{),}
                                \DataTypeTok{index =} \NormalTok{my.index)}

\CommentTok{# print result}
\KeywordTok{print}\NormalTok{(my.hausman.test.train.lag)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## 
##  Hausman Test
## 
## data:  my.lag.formula
## chisq = 289.55, df = 7, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: one model is inconsistent
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Wouldn't low p-value mean we should go with fixed effect instead of random? But just including within doesn't work below. }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Then, we build the model on the training set and predict on the test set
in order to calculate the MAPE.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my.pdm.train.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{plm}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{data =} \NormalTok{Full_data_long_train, }
                    \DataTypeTok{formula =} \NormalTok{my.lag.formula, }
                    \DataTypeTok{model =} \StringTok{'random'}\NormalTok{,}
                    \DataTypeTok{index =} \NormalTok{my.index)}
\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(my.pdm.train.lag)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}

##     index = my.index)

## 
## Effects:
##                   var std.dev share

## 
## Residuals:
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -142.410   -4.848    0.001    0.009    5.213  132.569 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                      Estimate  Std. Error   t-value  Pr(>|t|)

## lag(rentprice, 1)  1.00093673  0.00017581 5693.3592 < 2.2e-16 ***
## starsav           -0.25238363  0.14094489   -1.7907  0.073359 .  
## is_openave         3.34976459  0.48784817    6.8664 6.715e-12 ***
## funnyav           -0.49065915  0.15640230   -3.1372  0.001708 **

## ---

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Predict }
\NormalTok{Full_data_long_test$pred.plm.test.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{predict}\NormalTok{(my.pdm.train.lag, Full_data_long_test, }\DataTypeTok{type=}\StringTok{'response'}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# MAPE}
\NormalTok{plmmape.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{*}\KeywordTok{mean}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{abs}\NormalTok{(Full_data_long_test$pred.plm.test.lag/Full_data_long_test$rentprice}\DecValTok{-1}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =} \NormalTok{T)}

\begin{Shaded}

\NormalTok{Full_data_long <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Full_data_long[-}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{40}\NormalTok{)]}
\NormalTok{Imputed_Full_data_long <-}\KeywordTok{amelia}\NormalTok{(Full_data_long,}\DataTypeTok{ts=} \StringTok{'time'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{cs=} \StringTok{'postal_code'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{p2s=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{intercs =} \OtherTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{idvars=}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'City'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'State'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'Metro'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'CountyName'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'year'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'month'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'YearMonth'}\NormalTok{))}

\KeywordTok{write.amelia}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{obj=}\NormalTok{Imputed_Full_data_long, }\DataTypeTok{file.stem=}\StringTok{"imputedfull"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{data1 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"imputedfull1.csv"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{data2 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"imputedfull2.csv"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{data5 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"imputedfull5.csv"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{data1 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(data1, }\DataTypeTok{index =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"postal_code"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"time"}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{data2 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(data2, }\DataTypeTok{index =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"postal_code"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"time"}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{data3 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(data3, }\DataTypeTok{index =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"postal_code"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"time"}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{data4 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(data4, }\DataTypeTok{index =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"postal_code"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"time"}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{data5 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{pdata.frame}\NormalTok{(data5, }\DataTypeTok{index =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"postal_code"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"time"}\NormalTok{))}

\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now, we will create the train and tests set using the last 12 months (1
year) for the test set, but with imputed values.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{data5$time <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(data5$time, }\StringTok{"%Y-%m-%d"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{data5_train <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{data5[data5$time <}\StringTok{ "2017-01-01"}\NormalTok{,]}
\NormalTok{data5_test <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{data5[data5$time >=}\StringTok{ "2017-01-01"}\NormalTok{,]}

\NormalTok{my.formula.impute.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{rentprice ~}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{lag}\NormalTok{(rentprice, }\DecValTok{12}\NormalTok{) +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{starsav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{starssd +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{is_openave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{funnyav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{coolav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{usefulav +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Number_of_reviews +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Number_of_businesses +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Friday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Monday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Saturday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Sunday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Thursday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Tuesday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Wednesday_ave +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Friday_total +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Monday_total +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Saturday_total +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Sunday_total +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Thursday_total +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Tuesday_total +}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Wednesday_total}

\NormalTok{my.index <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'postal_code'}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{'time'}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Conduct Hausman Test}
\NormalTok{my.hausman.test.train.impute.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{phtest}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =} \NormalTok{my.formula.impute.lag, }
                                           \DataTypeTok{data =} \NormalTok{data5_train, }
                                           \DataTypeTok{model =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'within'}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{'random'}\NormalTok{),}
                                           \DataTypeTok{index =} \NormalTok{my.index)}
\CommentTok{# print result}
\KeywordTok{print}\NormalTok{(my.hausman.test.train.impute.lag)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

##  Hausman Test
## 
## data:  my.formula.impute.lag
## chisq = 26426, df = 23, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: one model is inconsistent
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Low p-value, but we'll go with random. }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Build random effects model on train and predict on test.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my.pdm.train.impute.lag <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{plm}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{data =} \NormalTok{data5_train, }
                    \DataTypeTok{formula =} \NormalTok{my.formula.impute.lag, }
                    \DataTypeTok{model =} \StringTok{'random'}\NormalTok{,}
                    \DataTypeTok{index =} \NormalTok{my.index)}
\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(my.pdm.train.impute.lag)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{Final Model}\label{final-model}

The last thing we do is subset the Business dataset to include only
businesses categorized as food or bars. We do this because we expect
these businesses to have a stronger relationship to rent prices than
others, such as Beauty \& Spas.
